1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,400
Oh, but you don't understand, she said.

2
00:00:00,670 --> 00:00:05,360
Mr. W, me, doesn't stand for anyone being drunk on the job.

3
00:00:05,470 --> 00:00:08,400
Jim's lost his job and now what will we do?

4
00:00:08,670 --> 00:00:11,200
I told her Jim wouldn't be dismissed.

5
00:00:11,310 --> 00:00:12,880
She asked how I knew.

6
00:00:12,990 --> 00:00:19,200
The reason I explained is because I'm Mr. W. She almost fainted.

7
00:00:19,390 --> 00:00:23,039
I told her I'd do all I could to help Jim at the plant,

8
00:00:23,070 --> 00:00:28,720
and I hoped she'd do all she could at home, and just have him on the job in the morning.

9
00:00:29,390 --> 00:00:34,880
When I got back to the plant, I went down to Jim's department and spoke to Jim's co-workers.

10
00:00:34,990 --> 00:00:40,079
I told them, you've seen something unpleasant here today, but I want you to forget it.

11
00:00:40,190 --> 00:00:41,920
Jim will be back tomorrow.

12
00:00:42,029 --> 00:00:43,279
Be kind to him.

13
00:00:43,470 --> 00:00:48,880
He's been a good worker for a long time, and we owe it to him to give him another chance.

14
00:00:49,870 --> 00:00:54,160
Jim got back on the ball, and his drinking was never again a problem.

15
00:00:54,269 --> 00:00:56,319
I soon forgot about the incident.

16
00:00:56,430 --> 00:00:57,839
But Jim didn't.

17
00:00:58,110 --> 00:01:05,279
Two years ago, the headquarters of the local union sent some men here to negotiate the contract for the local.

18
00:01:05,630 --> 00:01:09,440
They had some staggering, simply unrealistic demands.

19
00:01:09,710 --> 00:01:13,759
Jim, quiet, meek Jim, suddenly became a leader.

20
00:01:13,950 --> 00:01:20,319
He got busy and reminded the fellows in the plant that they'd always gotten a fair deal from Mr. W.,

21
00:01:20,350 --> 00:01:24,880
and we didn't need outsiders coming to tell us how to run our affairs.

22
00:01:25,630 --> 00:01:32,240
The outsiders left, and as usual we negotiated our contract like friends, thanks to Jim.

23
00:01:33,150 --> 00:01:37,920
Here are two ways to use the Be Human approach to make you a better leader.

24
00:01:38,110 --> 00:01:46,400
First, each time you face a difficult matter involving people, ask yourself, what is the human way to handle this?

25
00:01:47,070 --> 00:01:54,319
Ponder over this question when there is a disagreement among your subordinates or when an employee creates a problem.

26
00:01:55,070 --> 00:01:59,519
Remember Bob W.'s formula for helping others correct their mistakes.

27
00:01:59,710 --> 00:02:01,120
Avoid sarcasm.

28
00:02:01,230 --> 00:02:02,880
Avoid being cynical.

29
00:02:03,070 --> 00:02:05,759
Avoid taking people down a peg or two.

30
00:02:05,870 --> 00:02:08,160
Avoid putting others in their place.

31
00:02:08,509 --> 00:02:12,160
Ask, what is the human way to deal with people?

32
00:02:12,430 --> 00:02:13,839
It always pays.

33
00:02:13,950 --> 00:02:16,400
Sometimes sooner, sometimes later.

34
00:02:16,509 --> 00:02:18,240
But it always pays.

35
00:02:18,990 --> 00:02:26,480
A second way to profit from the Be Human rule is to let your actions show you put people first.

36
00:02:27,150 --> 00:02:31,039
Show interest in your subordinates' off-the-job accomplishments.

37
00:02:31,230 --> 00:02:33,039
Treat everyone with dignity.

38
00:02:33,150 --> 00:02:37,440
Remind yourself that the primary purpose in life is to enjoy it.

39
00:02:37,789 --> 00:02:43,200
As a general rule, the more interest you show in a person, the more he will produce for you,

40
00:02:43,310 --> 00:02:48,480
and his production is what carries you forward to greater and greater success.

41
00:02:49,230 --> 00:02:55,039
Praise your subordinates to your supervisor by putting in plugs for them at every opportunity.

42
00:02:55,230 --> 00:03:00,400
It's an old American custom to admire the fellow who's on the side of the little man.

43
00:03:00,670 --> 00:03:05,759
Your subordinates will appreciate your plugs, and their loyalty to you will grow.

44
00:03:06,190 --> 00:03:11,600
And do not fear that this will lower your own importance in the eyes of your supervisor.

45
00:03:11,870 --> 00:03:21,200
Rather, a man big enough to be humble appears more confident than the insecure man who feels compelled to call attention to his accomplishments.

46
00:03:21,470 --> 00:03:24,240
A little modesty goes a long way.

47
00:03:25,390 --> 00:03:29,039
Praise your subordinates personally at every opportunity.

48
00:03:29,230 --> 00:03:31,279
Praise them for their cooperation.

49
00:03:31,470 --> 00:03:34,960
Praise them for every extra effort they put forth.

50
00:03:35,390 --> 00:03:41,120
Praise is the greatest single incentive you can give people, and it costs you nothing.

51
00:03:41,550 --> 00:03:47,039
Besides, a write-in vote has often overthrown a powerful known candidate.

52
00:03:47,310 --> 00:03:52,640
You never know when your subordinates can do you a turn by coming to your defense.

53
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:55,039
Practice praising people.

54
00:03:55,390 --> 00:03:57,360
Rub people the right way.

55
00:03:57,710 --> 00:04:00,910
Be human.
